indeed the best known of all his works ; that by which almost alone he keeps a place in the thoughts of any besides professed students of history or theology. There aro scenos in it which live in the hearts of every one of us: the picture of the Anglian slave boys in the Roman Forum, whose fair angelic faces first stirred in the heart of Gregory the desire to save from the wrath of God the souls that dwelt within such heavenly forms¹ ; the story of the Northumbrian thane who gave his voice for the intro- duction of Christianity, in the hope that it would throw some light on the dark problems of existence, the whence and the whither of the human soul, which seemed to him like a sparrow which flits in winter through a lighted hall, passing from darkness into darkness23 the descrip-
